er der Demokratie werden.  aPoststructuralism deconstructs liberal-democratic concepts and rejects ultimate justifications for normative ordering. For this reason, critics accuse it of being incompatible with a democratic position. Derrida, Butler, Laclau, and Mouffe represent, however, a radical future form of democracy. How can this 'ethical turn' be evaluated? How did these scholars derive reasons for democracy from an alleged groundlessness? Luzia Sievi delivers a detailed analysis of both the critiques of democracy as well as the above-mentioned thinkers' outlines of democracy. In doing so, she shows the values and findings which caused harsh critics of democracy to become strong advocates for it.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 3.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/3.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 4aChantal Mouffe. 4aDekonstruktivismus. 4aErnesto Laclau. 4aJacques Derrida. 4aJudith Butler. 4aPhilosophie. 4aPolitik. 4aPolitikwissenschaft. 4aPolitische Philosophie. 4aPolitische Theorie. 4aPoststrukturalismus. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh  aChantal Mouffe.  aDeconstructivism.  aErnesto Laclau.  aJacques Derrida.  aJudith Butler.  aPhilosophy.  aPolitical Philosophy.  aPolitical Science.  aPolitical Theory.  aPolitics.  aPost-structuralism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2017z978311071954340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9783839437919zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de GruyterzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783839437919zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783839437919/original  a978-3-11-071954-3 DG Plus eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-al